# sentence_id = 27
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 3.6
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = For they say they themselves call the outlying villages "kōmai," whereas Athenians call them "dēmoi"; and they imply that comedians were so named not from "kōmazein" (to revel), but because of their wandering through villages ("kōmai") when they were held in no honor in the city. They also say that they themselves use "drān" for "to do," while Athenians use "prattein." Let this much be said about the differences of imitation, how many and what they are.
# literal_translation = Themselves indeed for villages the outlying to-call they-say, Athenians but demes, as comedians not from the to-revel being-called but to-the according-to villages wandering being-dishonored from the city; and the to-do themselves indeed dran, Athenians but prattein to-address. Concerning indeed then the differences and how-many and what-sorts of-the imitation let-it-be-said these.
