# sentence_id = 109
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 8.3
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = Homer, however, just as he is superior in other respects, also seems to have seen this point well, whether by art or by nature. For in composing the Odyssey, he did not include everything that happened to Odysseus, such as his being wounded on Parnassus or his feigning madness at the muster, things where the occurrence of one did not make the occurrence of the other necessary or probable, but he constructed the Odyssey around a single action of the kind we speak of, and similarly also the Iliad.
# literal_translation = the but Homer just-as also the others differs and this seems well to-see, either through art or through nature; Odyssey for making not he-made all as-many-as to-him happened, such-as to-be-wounded indeed in the Parnassus, to-be-mad but to-pretend in the muster, of-which nothing of-the-other having-happened necessary was or likely the-other to-become, but about one action of-what-sort we-say the Odyssey he-constructed, similarly but also the Iliad.
