# sentence_id = 110
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 8.4
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = As, therefore, in the other imitative arts, a single imitation is an imitation of a single object, so the plot, since it is an imitation of an action, must be an imitation of one and that a whole action; and the parts of the incidents must be so constructed that if any part is displaced or removed, the whole is disjointed and disturbed. For that which makes no perceptible difference by its presence or absence is no part of the whole.
# literal_translation = It-is-necessary therefore, just-as also in the other imitative-arts the one imitation of-one is, so also the plot, since of-action imitation is, of-one both to-be and of-this whole, and the parts to-be-composed of-the things so as-to of-being-displaced of-certain part or of-being-removed to-differ and to-be-moved the whole; what for being-present or not being-present nothing makes manifest, nothing part of-the whole is.
