# sentence_id = 121
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 9.11
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = Of all plots and actions, the episodic are the worst. I call a plot 'episodic' in which the episodes follow one another without probable or necessary sequence. Bad poets compose such plots through their own lack of skill; good poets, on account of the actors; for in composing entries for a contest, and stretching the plot beyond its capacity, they are often forced to distort the sequence. Since Tragedy is an imitation not only of a complete action, but of events inspiring fear and pity, these effects are produced best when events occur unexpectedly and yet as a consequence of one another.
# literal_translation = of-the but simple plots and actions the episodic are worst; I-speak but episodic plot, in which the episodes after each-other neither likely nor necessity to-be; such but are-made by indeed the mean poets through themselves, by but the good through the actors; contest-pieces for making and beside the power stretching the plot often to-distort they-are-forced the in-sequence. Since but not only of-complete is of-action the imitation but and of-fearful and of-pitiful, these but becomes and especially and more whenever it-becomes beside the opinion through each-other.
