# sentence_id = 195
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 15.11
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = Since tragedy is an imitation of people better than we are, one should imitate the good portrait-painters; for while they reproduce the specific shape and make people like [the originals], they paint them more beautiful. So too the poet, in imitating people who are irascible or easy-going or have other such traits of character, should make them decent while remaining like that; [an example of harshness is Achilles as made good by Homer].
# literal_translation = Since but imitation is the tragedy of better [people] than we , it is necessary to imitate the good portrait-painters ; and for those attributing the own form like making better they paint ; thus also the poet imitating both irascible and easy-going and the other the such having in the characters such being decent to make † example of harshness such as the Achilles good and Homer † .
