# sentence_id = 205
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 16.9
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = The fourth is through reasoning, as in the Choephoroe, that someone like [himself] has come, but no one is like him except Orestes, therefore he has come. And that of Polyidus the sophist regarding the Iphigenia: for it is natural, he said, for Orestes to reason that his sister was sacrificed and it is now his turn to be sacrificed. And in the Tydeus of Theodectes, that having come to find his son, he himself is destroyed. And the one in the Phineidae: for upon seeing the place they reasoned their fate, that it was fated for them to die in this place, for they were exposed there.
# literal_translation = fourth but the from reasoning , such-as in Choephoroe , that like someone has-come , like but no-one but or Orestes , this therefore has-come . and the of-Polyidus the of-the sophist concerning of-the Iphigenia ; likely for he-said the Orestes to-reason that the and sister was-sacrificed and to-him it-happens to-be-sacrificed . and in the of-Theodectes Tydeus , that having-come as to-find the son himself is-destroyed . and the in the Phineidae ; having-seen for the place they-reasoned the fate that in this it-was-fated to-die to-them , and for they-were-exposed there .
