# sentence_id = 296
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 22.9
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = So those are not right who criticize this mode of speech and ridicule the poet, like the elder Euclid, who said it is easy to write poetry if one is allowed to lengthen words as much as one likes, parodying the style in these very words: "I saw Epichares walking to Marathon," and "not... his hellebore."
# literal_translation = so-as not rightly they-blame the-ones criticizing to-the such mode of-the dialect and ridiculing the poet , such-as Euclid the ancient , as easy being to-make if someone will-give to-lengthen over as-much-as he-wishes , having-composed-iambics in itself the diction " Epichares I-saw to-Marathon walking , " and " not † would having-become † the of-that hellebore . "
