# sentence_id = 300
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 22.13
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = If one inserts ordinary words in place of rare words, metaphors, and the other forms, one can see that what we say is true. For instance, Aeschylus and Euripides composed the same iambic line, but by changing only a single word—replacing a common, ordinary term with a rare one—one line appears beautiful and the other mean. Aeschylus in his Philoctetes wrote: "The ulcer that eats the flesh of my foot," but Euripides changed "eats" to "feasts upon." And if in the line: "Now one who is small and of no worth and unseemly," one were to replace the words with ordinary ones: "Now one who is little and weak and ugly." And: "Having set down an unseemly chair and a small table," with: "Having set down a wretched chair and a tiny table." And replacing "the shores cry out" with "the shores shout."
# literal_translation = and upon of-the rare-word but and upon of-the metaphors and upon of-the other forms having-transposed if someone the ordinary nouns he-would-perceive that true we-say ; such-as the same having-made iambic of-Aeschylus and of-Euripides , one but only noun having-transposed , instead of-ordinary customary rare-word , the on-the-one-hand appears beautiful the but mean . Aeschylus on-the-one-hand for in the Philoctetes made " ulcer which of-me flesh eats of-foot , " the but instead of-the eats the feasts-upon transposed . and " now but me being small and of-no-worth and unseemly , " if someone would-say the ordinary having-transposed " now but me being little and weak and ugly ; " and " chair unseemly having-set-down small and table , " " chair wretched having-set-down tiny and table ; " and the " shores cry-out , " shores shout .
