# sentence_id = 328
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 24.14
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = For the poet himself should speak as little as possible; for in those parts he is not an imitator. Now the other poets compete in their own persons throughout, and imitate only a few things and only rarely; but he, after a few words of introduction, immediately brings in a man or a woman or some other character, and none of them is characterless, but all have character.
# literal_translation = Himself for it-is-necessary the poet least to-speak; not for he-is according-to these imitator. The on-the-one-hand therefore others self on-the-one-hand through whole compete, they-imitate but few and rarely; he but few having-preluded immediately introduces man or woman or other some character, and none-at-all characterless but having character.
