# sentence_id = 332
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 24.18
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = Homer especially has taught others how to tell lies as they ought. This is a paralogism. People think that when, if A exists or happens, B exists or happens, then if B exists, A must also exist or happen. This is false. Therefore, if the first thing is false, but if it were true some other thing would necessarily exist or happen, one should add it; for because our mind knows this latter is true, it falsely reasons that the first is also true. An example of this is from the Bath-scene.
# literal_translation = Has-taught but most Homer and the others false-things to-speak as it-is-necessary. It-is but this paralogism. They-think for the men, whenever this-thing being that-thing is or becoming becomes, if the later is, and the earlier to-be or to-become; this-thing but is false. Wherefore it-is-necessary, if the first false, other but of-this being necessity to-be or to-become be, to-add; through for the this to-know true being paralogizes of-us the soul and the first as being. Example but of-this the from the of-Washings.
