# sentence_id = 334
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 24.20
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = Plots should not be composed of irrational parts; ideally, they should have nothing irrational in them, or, if they must, it should be outside the plot, like Oedipus not knowing how Laius died, and not in the drama itself, like the reports of the Pythian games in Electra or the man coming speechless from Tegea to Mysia in the Mysians.
# literal_translation = The and plots not to-be-composed from parts irrational, but most on-the-one-hand nothing to-have irrational, if but not, outside of-the plot, as Oedipus the not to-know how the Laius died, but not in the drama, as in Electra the the Pythian-games reporting or in Mysians the speechless from Tegea into the Mysia coming.
