# sentence_id = 352
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 25.15
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = As to whether something has been well or not well said or done by someone, we must not only look at the act or word itself to see if it is good or bad, but also at the person doing or saying it, to whom, when, by what means, or for what end—for instance, for the sake of a greater good to come about or a greater evil to be avoided.
# literal_translation = Concerning but of-the well or not well if it-has-been-said by-someone or it-has-been-done, not only considering toward self the thing-done or thing-said looking if excellent or bad, but also toward the doing or saying toward whom or when or to-whom or of-which for-sake, such-as if of-greater good, in-order-that it-becomes, or of-greater evil, in-order-that it-is-removed.
