# sentence_id = 353
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 25.16
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = Difficulties concerning diction must be solved by looking at the specific word, for example a rare word: 'mules (ourēas) first'; for perhaps he does not mean mules but guards. And of Dolon, 'who was indeed in form (eidos) bad,' not that his body was asymmetrical but his face was ugly, for the Cretans call a handsome face 'eu-eides'. And 'mix the drink stronger (zōroteron)' means not unmixed as for drunkards but more quickly.
# literal_translation = The but toward the diction looking it-is-necessary to-solve, such-as by-tongue the «mules on-the-one-hand first»; perhaps for not the mules he-says but the guards; and the Dolon, «who truly in-form on-the-one-hand he-was bad», not the body asymmetrical but the face ugly, the for handsome-faced the Cretans the good-faced they-call; and the «stronger but mix» not the unmixed as for-drunkards but the faster.
