# sentence_id = 354
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 25.17
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = Other things are said metaphorically, such as 'all gods and men slept all night long,' yet he says at the same time 'when indeed he looked toward the Trojan plain, the noise of flutes and pipes'; for 'all' is said metaphorically for 'many,' as 'all' is a kind of 'many.' And 'alone without a share' is metaphorical, for 'the best known' is alone.
# literal_translation = The but according-to metaphor it-has-been-said, such-as «all truly then gods both and men they-slept all-night»; at-the-same-time but he-says «truly when toward plain the Trojan he-might-look-at, of-flutes of-pipes both noise»; the for all instead-of of-the many according-to metaphor it-has-been-said, the for all much something. And the «alone but without-share» according-to metaphor, the for best-known only.
