# sentence_id = 375
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 26.6
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = If then it is vulgar, it would clearly be inferior. First, the accusation is not against the art of poetry but against the art of acting, since it is possible to overdo the signs even when reciting epic, which Sosistratus did, and when singing, which Mnasitheus of Opus used to do.
# literal_translation = If therefore vulgar, worse clear that would it-might-be. First on-the-one-hand not of-the poetic-art the accusation but of-the acting, since it-is to-be-over-elaborate with-the signs and rhapsodizing, which is Sosistratus, and singing-through, which he-did Mnasitheus the Opuntian.
